    "summary": "Petra (c. 312–106 BC as [[event:1145|Nabataean Kingdom]] capital) is an archaeological city carved into rose-red sandstone cliffs in southern Jordan, the capital of the Nabataean civilization and a UNESCO World Heritage Site often called the 'Rose City' — one of the most spectacular human-made environments in the ancient world and a testament to the Nabataeans' mastery of rock-carving and hydraulic engineering.\n\nPetra grew around a natural rock basin approached through a narrow gorge (the Siq), which provided natural defense. Its most famous monuments — the Treasury (Al-Khazneh), the Monastery (Ad-Deir), and dozens of elaborately carved royal tombs — were cut directly into the sandstone cliffs, blending Hellenistic architectural styles with local Arabian traditions. The city supported tens of thousands of inhabitants through an elaborate water system of cisterns, channels, and dams that collected and distributed scarce rainfall. Its streets were lined with colonnaded structures, temples, and markets that reflected the wealth generated by controlling caravan routes. The city was largely abandoned after Rome redirected trade routes and a major earthquake in 363 AD damaged its water systems. Petra was 'rediscovered' by the Western world by the Swiss explorer Johann Burckhardt in 1812.",
